WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.360
Hi everybody, I'm so excited to be here speaking at posit.conf, and I'm even more excited that

00:00:12.360 --> 00:00:20.840
you all are sticking around for the very last session of posit.conf.

00:00:20.840 --> 00:00:26.760
So I work for the State Department of Agriculture in the state of Washington, and we've collected

00:00:26.760 --> 00:00:32.040
almost 900 different soil samples from all across the state.

00:00:32.040 --> 00:00:37.959
And every single one of those farmers or land managers gets their very own custom soil health

00:00:37.959 --> 00:00:39.040
report.

00:00:39.040 --> 00:00:44.119
And this is going to help them understand the soil health in their fields, and they

00:00:44.119 --> 00:00:49.279
can make decisions on how to manage their fields based on these reports, based on this

00:00:49.279 --> 00:00:50.779
data.

00:00:50.779 --> 00:00:52.119
How did we do this?

00:00:52.119 --> 00:00:56.759
We used parameterized reporting with Quarto.

00:00:56.759 --> 00:00:58.680
So maybe you don't care about soils.

00:00:58.680 --> 00:01:02.360
I've only met one person at this conference who also works in soils.

00:01:02.360 --> 00:01:07.559
So I want to point out some other examples of how you can use parameterized reporting.

00:01:07.559 --> 00:01:14.260
So there's examples of mapping ocean floors, making fiscal briefs, or figuring out which

00:01:14.260 --> 00:01:17.279
state has the worst drivers.

00:01:17.279 --> 00:01:23.800
So there's all sorts of different ways that you can use parameterized reports.

00:01:23.800 --> 00:01:25.120
Now why should you listen to me?

00:01:25.120 --> 00:01:31.160
I have zero computer science background, I have no coding background, but I absolutely

00:01:31.160 --> 00:01:34.959
love automating things, and I love making beautiful products.

00:01:34.959 --> 00:01:39.239
So originally, when I started at the State Department of Agriculture, I was hired as

00:01:39.239 --> 00:01:41.279
just an environmental technician.

00:01:41.279 --> 00:01:46.040
I scooped water out of streams that would get tested for pesticides.

00:01:46.040 --> 00:01:54.400
So eventually, though, I started to teach myself some basic R data wrangling and visualization,

00:01:54.400 --> 00:01:59.160
and I applied for a data scientist job in our soil section.

00:01:59.160 --> 00:02:05.480
So I went from water quality and field work to soils and data science.

00:02:05.480 --> 00:02:11.039
And this is really cool because I got to go from picking leeches off of my boots to picking

00:02:11.039 --> 00:02:15.039
cats off of my keyboard.

00:02:15.039 --> 00:02:22.399
So you're probably wondering now, how did I go from being a non-coder to a data scientist?

00:02:22.399 --> 00:02:25.759
And the answer is a skills test.

00:02:25.759 --> 00:02:32.080
I had the opportunity to learn something new, parameterized reporting, and demonstrate this

00:02:32.080 --> 00:02:38.919
ability through this skills test, where I had to create custom soil health reports for

00:02:38.919 --> 00:02:42.199
86 different farmers.

00:02:42.199 --> 00:02:44.440
And I had one week to do this.

00:02:44.440 --> 00:02:48.279
I had no idea what a parameterized report was.

00:02:48.279 --> 00:02:51.279
I was kind of freaking out.

00:02:51.279 --> 00:02:54.639
I was wondering, how do I automate reports?

00:02:54.639 --> 00:02:57.880
And I sort of felt some existential dread.

00:02:57.880 --> 00:03:02.360
And I was wondering, have I made the wrong decisions in life?

00:03:02.360 --> 00:03:04.800
Am I in over my head?

00:03:04.800 --> 00:03:09.720
But lucky for me, the RStats community is so amazing.

00:03:09.880 --> 00:03:16.360
I was able to go down so many different rabbit holes and looking at YouTube videos and blog

00:03:16.360 --> 00:03:17.880
posts.

00:03:17.880 --> 00:03:20.800
And I went through a bit of tutorial how.

00:03:20.800 --> 00:03:28.000
But that all got me to this place where I was able to create these reports with parameterized

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:29.960
R markdown.

00:03:29.960 --> 00:03:30.960
In one week.

00:03:30.960 --> 00:03:31.960
So...

00:03:31.960 --> 00:03:41.639
These are the reports that essentially got me my job and got me out of the streams and

00:03:41.639 --> 00:03:45.360
behind a computer where I get to just chill with my cats all day.

00:03:45.360 --> 00:03:46.360
And work.

00:03:46.360 --> 00:03:48.600
In case my boss is watching this.

00:03:48.600 --> 00:03:50.279
Okay.

00:03:50.279 --> 00:03:52.759
So fast forward to two years later.

00:03:52.759 --> 00:03:54.720
We're in 2023.

00:03:54.720 --> 00:03:56.919
And we've switched to Corto.

00:03:56.919 --> 00:04:03.759
Because I went to RStudioConf 2022 and learned about Corto and was just so excited.

00:04:03.759 --> 00:04:10.320
So in 2023, we now have HTML reports where we're using leaflet, we're using Plotly.

00:04:10.320 --> 00:04:13.800
And now we have these cool interactive reports.

00:04:13.800 --> 00:04:18.640
But there's some people who would rather just have a physical piece of paper.

