outputs.

00:04:27.119 --> 00:04:31.600
Which I then manually converted to PDF.

00:04:31.600 --> 00:04:35.880
Because I didn't want to learn LaTeX.

00:04:35.880 --> 00:04:42.079
And Microsoft Word is so easy to make template reports that have just out of the box beautiful

00:04:42.079 --> 00:04:43.959
styling.

00:04:43.959 --> 00:04:50.920
So this talk is the very last session of the conference.

00:04:50.920 --> 00:04:52.239
I'm tired.

00:04:52.239 --> 00:04:53.959
You're probably all tired.

00:04:53.959 --> 00:04:54.959
Our brains are full.

00:04:55.279 --> 00:04:57.399
So if you want to take a nap, please feel free.

00:04:57.399 --> 00:05:03.880
Because I have all the slides available at the tiny URL link in this QR code.

00:05:03.880 --> 00:05:07.920
But I'm going to have a lot of code snippets that I'm not going to have time to walk through.

00:05:07.920 --> 00:05:09.799
So I've included them.

00:05:09.799 --> 00:05:14.640
And you'll have to take a look later on in the slides.

00:05:14.640 --> 00:05:16.200
Okay.

00:05:16.200 --> 00:05:20.239
So there's a generalized four-step workflow.

00:05:20.239 --> 00:05:25.440
From the perspective of a self-taught slash community-taught R user.

00:05:25.440 --> 00:05:28.600
Where I first had to learn what is parameterized reporting.

00:05:28.600 --> 00:05:32.200
So we'll go through a bit of parameterized reporting 101.

00:05:32.200 --> 00:05:34.600
And then we're going to talk about subsettable data.

00:05:34.600 --> 00:05:39.359
And how to get our data ready for parameterized reports.

00:05:39.359 --> 00:05:44.959
And then we'll talk about making sure that our content is interpretable and understandable

00:05:44.959 --> 00:05:46.799
to our readers.

00:05:46.799 --> 00:05:48.179
And also accessible.

00:05:48.179 --> 00:05:51.980
So our font sizes, color contrast.

00:05:51.980 --> 00:05:57.899
And for the Python users in the room, the parameterized Quarto reports can also be used

00:05:57.899 --> 00:06:01.059
with the Jupyter engine as well as the Knitter engine.

00:06:01.059 --> 00:06:07.420
So take a look at the Quarto docs for the syntax differences.

00:06:07.420 --> 00:06:09.279
Okay.

00:06:09.279 --> 00:06:13.519
So step one is learning about parameterized reports.

00:06:13.519 --> 00:06:15.459
So what is it?

00:06:15.459 --> 00:06:20.619
It's essentially a template report where it's going to have placeholders where you can then

00:06:20.619 --> 00:06:23.980
fill in whatever values you need.

00:06:23.980 --> 00:06:28.779
So what really helped me to think of parameterized reports as functions.

00:06:28.779 --> 00:06:30.420
Like really complex functions.

00:06:30.420 --> 00:06:37.700
So imagine you have a Quarto file and you're trying to report something for every single

00:06:37.700 --> 00:06:38.700
year.

00:06:38.700 --> 00:06:44.859
So this function or this template is going to take in parameters as the function input,

00:06:44.859 --> 00:06:45.859
essentially.

00:06:45.859 --> 00:06:51.100
So if you were producing all these reports for each year, instead of going through and

00:06:51.100 --> 00:06:58.940
changing 2019 to 2020 to 2021, you're going to put in params, dollars, and year.

00:06:58.940 --> 00:07:03.959
And then the output of your function are going to be these reports for every single year

00:07:03.959 --> 00:07:05.940
without copying and pasting.

00:07:05.940 --> 00:07:07.459
It's amazing.

00:07:07.459 --> 00:07:08.660
Okay.

00:07:08.660 --> 00:07:14.339
So for your parameterized report, you'll have a YAML header, which stands for yet another

00:07:14.339 --> 00:07:16.179
markdown language.

00:07:16.179 --> 00:07:19.820
And this YAML header is going to contain your basic metadata.

00:07:19.820 --> 00:07:25.220
So your title, subtitle, date, author, that fun information.

00:07:25.220 --> 00:07:28.339
It'll also be where you specify your format types.

00:07:28.339 --> 00:07:32.980
So in our case, we output to HTML and Word doc.

00:07:32.980 --> 00:07:35.940
And this is also where you're going to set your parameters.

00:07:35.940 --> 00:07:39.779
So these are key value pairs where you're naming your parameters.

00:07:39.779 --> 00:07:45.700
And then you're also naming the default value that it will use.

00:07:45.700 --> 00:07:51.059
Below your YAML header is going to be your basic report content.

00:07:51.059 --> 00:07:53.859
Now how do you access your parameters?

00:07:53.859 --> 00:07:58.899
If you're working in RStudio interactively, you can run any line or code chunk.

00:07:58.899 --> 00:08:04.739
And this is going to add this params object to your environment.

00:08:04.739 --> 00:08:11.980
And then because this is just a list object, you can use the standard list notation and

00:08:11.980 --> 00:08:15.859
access these parameters with params$farmer.

00:08:15.859 --> 00:08:19.820
And then that would give you, like, Sammy Sunflower.

00:08:19.820 --> 00:08:22.220
And you can also use parameters for inline code.

00:08:22.220 --> 00:08:28.299
So if you enclose your expression in backtick R, your expression backtick, it will dynamically

00:08:28.299 --> 00:08:31.820
calculate or render whatever your parameter is.

00:08:31.820 --> 00:08:39.340
So for example, we have these are results for params$farmer, Sammy Sunflower.

00:08:39.340 --> 00:08:41.179
Now how do you render the reports?

00:08:41.179 --> 00:08:48.340
So the fastest way to just iterate over your reports and edit and get the look and the

00:08:48.340 --> 00:08:53.380
feel right is using the IDE and using the render button.

00:08:53.380 --> 00:08:58.940
And if you hit the little arrow, you can choose between all the different outputs that you've

00:08:58.940 --> 00:09:02.739
specified in your YAML.

00:09:02.739 --> 00:09:08.219
If you like hotkeys or keyboard shortcuts like I do, you can use control shift K, and

00:09:08.219 --> 00:09:10.099
that's super helpful.

00:09:10.099 --> 00:09:16.659
And another nifty feature is the render on save option, where if you have that checked,

00:09:16.659 --> 00:09:20.659
every time you save your file, it's going to re-render that report.

00:09:20.659 --> 00:09:27.940
And then you'll be able to see your HTML preview update if you're rendering to HTML.

00:09:27.940 --> 00:09:33.979
And it should be noted that this way of rendering these reports are going to use your default

00:09:33.979 --> 00:09:37.619
parameters that you've specified in your YAML.

00:09:37.619 --> 00:09:42.340
And it's also going to have the same name and the output file location as the input

00:09:42.340 --> 00:09:44.260
file.

00:09:44.260 --> 00:09:51.700
Now you can also programmatically render your Quarto files using the Quarto render function.

00:09:51.700 --> 00:09:53.299
And this you would include.

00:09:53.299 --> 00:09:57.859
You would run this in your console or in a separate iterate.r script or whatever you

00:09:57.859 --> 00:09:59.299
want to call it.

00:09:59.299 --> 00:10:07.580
And you're going to specify your input file, your output format type, the output file name,

00:10:07.580 --> 00:10:11.739
and then your named list of parameters.

00:10:11.739 --> 00:10:16.820
And this is especially helpful for when you want to render all of your reports at one

00:10:16.820 --> 00:10:18.460
time.

00:10:18.460 --> 00:10:21.780
So to do this, we're going to create a data frame that has two columns.

00:10:21.780 --> 00:10:26.380
And these column names will match our Quarto render arguments.

00:10:26.380 --> 00:10:28.820
The first is output underscore file.

00:10:28.820 --> 00:10:33.700
And this will contain the file name with the extension.

00:10:33.700 --> 00:10:39.859
And then execute underscore params will have the named list of parameters.

00:10:39.859 --> 00:10:43.940
And so here's an example of code I'm not going to talk about, but you can check out later

00:10:43.940 --> 00:10:53.539
to get this basic two-column data frame that has the output files and the parameters.

00:10:53.539 --> 00:11:01.140
And we can use the perp walk function to iterate over each row of this report's data frame.

00:11:01.140 --> 00:11:05.500
And we'll just, again, specify the input file name and the output format, which is going

00:11:05.500 --> 00:11:12.140
to match the file extension that you had in this report's data frame.

00:11:12.140 --> 00:11:13.619
And this is where the magic happens.

00:11:14.299 --> 00:11:19.260
I've heard the term magic being said so many times at this conference.

00:11:19.260 --> 00:11:20.820
It's simply amazing.

00:11:20.820 --> 00:11:22.979
But seriously, it's pure magic.

00:11:22.979 --> 00:11:29.619
So this is all the files being knit back to back from one function call.

00:11:29.619 --> 00:11:33.700
And you can see all the documents are just being populated in the files pane.

00:11:33.700 --> 00:11:36.419
It is absolutely amazing.

00:11:37.140 --> 00:11:41.619
I figured that out at about 2 in the morning.

00:11:43.539 --> 00:11:45.059
I don't know why that was not hidden.

00:11:47.219 --> 00:11:52.020
But, yeah, I figured that out at 2 in the morning, the day I was supposed to turn in

00:11:52.020 --> 00:11:53.380
my skills test.

00:11:53.380 --> 00:11:59.299
And I ran into the bedroom, and I woke up my husband, and I was just so shocked and

00:11:59.299 --> 00:11:59.859
excited.

00:12:00.580 --> 00:12:02.900
Yeah, probably looks like Pikachu and my cat Mai.

00:12:03.460 --> 00:12:03.460


00:12:03.460 --> 00:12:07.539
So now we're going to talk about getting this data ready for our parameterized reports.

00:12:07.539 --> 00:12:10.419
So we're preparing data that is sub-settable.

00:12:10.419 --> 00:12:15.219
And this is just a simplified data frame where we have our year and our farmer.

00:12:15.219 --> 00:12:19.539
And these are, again, our parameters and some example data.

00:12:19.539 --> 00:12:23.700
And, yes, thanks, ChatGPT, for the punny farmer names.

00:12:23.700 --> 00:12:24.900
Punny farmer names.

00:12:28.260 --> 00:12:33.219
So you can use these params as basic values.

00:12:33.219 --> 00:12:39.140
So here we're just using declier filter and then setting our farmer equal to whatever

00:12:39.140 --> 00:12:40.739
that params value is.

00:12:41.460 --> 00:12:47.460
So we're doing some data wrangling here and creating a new column called category.

00:12:48.099 --> 00:12:53.140
And for each farmer that is being the report is being rendered for, that value would be

00:12:53.140 --> 00:12:54.340
your fields.

00:12:54.340 --> 00:12:59.619
For any samples that are in the same crop, it would be same crop.

00:12:59.619 --> 00:13:03.780
And then any other project, any other samples in the project would just be called other

00:13:03.780 --> 00:13:04.580
fields.

00:13:04.580 --> 00:13:08.900
And this is going to come in handy when we do our visualizations for our reports.

00:13:10.820 --> 00:13:12.900
So now we're going to create our content.

00:13:12.900 --> 00:13:18.820
So we want to make sure that it's easily consumed by whoever we are sending these reports to,

00:13:18.820 --> 00:13:23.140
that they're able to understand and make decisions based off of what you're showing

00:13:23.140 --> 00:13:23.380
them.

00:13:24.739 --> 00:13:31.780
So one way we did this was creating these static plots and interactive plots for HTML

00:13:31.780 --> 00:13:32.419
format.

00:13:32.419 --> 00:13:35.059
But we're now using that new category column.

00:13:35.619 --> 00:13:44.340
And we're styling each point so that it's really clear to the farmer which are their

00:13:44.340 --> 00:13:51.219
fields, which points are the fields that are in the same crop or the same county, and

00:13:51.219 --> 00:13:54.580
then just the general distribution of the project.

00:13:56.099 --> 00:14:03.059
And this helps people to interpret their data based on comparing it with other points.

00:14:03.059 --> 00:14:07.140
So we also want to make sure that our reports are self-contained.

00:14:07.140 --> 00:14:13.059
So we want to make sure that we are providing all the content for our readers to really

00:14:13.059 --> 00:14:15.299
understand the results that we're showing them.

00:14:16.739 --> 00:14:25.059
So we included about 30 different soil health measurements.

00:14:25.059 --> 00:14:32.500
And instead of including 300 lines of just regular text and prose of what these measurements

00:14:32.500 --> 00:14:40.179
were, we can use an includes shortcode that's actually going to just embed this other quarto

00:14:40.179 --> 00:14:46.580
document that's called soil health measurements into the parameterized parent quarto file.

00:14:46.580 --> 00:14:51.059
And it makes it so easy to reuse information across your different reports.

00:14:51.059 --> 00:14:53.380
And it shortens your main document.

00:14:54.659 --> 00:14:59.619
And I also mean self-contained in the more literal sense for the HTML reports, where

00:15:00.580 --> 00:15:05.460
we want to make sure that we can just send the HTML file, email it, whatever, and then

00:15:05.460 --> 00:15:08.979
the recipient can just open it off the bat.

00:15:08.979 --> 00:15:16.979
And so to do this, we'll do an include in YAML, or we'll do embed resources true in

00:15:16.979 --> 00:15:17.859
the YAML header.

00:15:17.859 --> 00:15:22.500
And what this is going to do is make sure that all the data, images, stylesheets, et

00:15:22.500 --> 00:15:24.979
cetera, are embedded into that file.

00:15:26.099 --> 00:15:33.059
Because otherwise, quarto is going to give you a underscore files folder that has all

00:15:33.059 --> 00:15:34.659
of those external dependencies.

00:15:34.659 --> 00:15:38.580
And if you send that with your HTML file, no one's going to know what to do with it.

00:15:38.580 --> 00:15:39.859
So make sure you embed.

00:15:41.380 --> 00:15:44.340
And then also, make sure you're mindful of size.

00:15:44.340 --> 00:15:50.260
So if you are doing these self-contained reports, don't make them too big that you can't email

00:15:50.260 --> 00:15:50.979
them.

00:15:50.979 --> 00:15:52.900
So just a heads up on there.

00:15:54.179 --> 00:15:54.580
OK.

00:15:54.580 --> 00:15:56.500
And then designing for accessibility.

00:15:56.500 --> 00:16:03.140
So I already talked about how we created HTML reports and PDF reports.

00:16:03.219 --> 00:16:08.099
So quarto makes this really easy by using these divs, where we can use this content

00:16:08.099 --> 00:16:10.260
visible when format is HTML.

00:16:10.900 --> 00:16:17.299
And this is really helpful when we want to use panel tab sets for just our HTML reports

00:16:17.299 --> 00:16:22.340
so that we don't have to have a whole long list on our HTML file.

00:16:22.340 --> 00:16:25.539
We can have tab sets for each category of our soil measurements.

00:16:26.500 --> 00:16:33.780
And for non-HTML files, we can use the content visible unless format HTML div.

00:16:33.780 --> 00:16:39.619
And now we just have our background information and a regular list of definitions.

00:16:41.059 --> 00:16:47.859
We also can use conditional code evaluation, where the code will only be evaluated if the

00:16:47.859 --> 00:16:49.380
output format is met.

00:16:49.940 --> 00:16:55.940
So, for example, if we wanted plotly code only for HTML or ggplot code for anything

00:16:55.940 --> 00:16:56.179
else.

00:16:56.900 --> 00:17:01.619
To do this, we're going to set an output format type in our setup chunk using this

00:17:01.619 --> 00:17:03.940
knitter ops knit get function.

00:17:05.939 --> 00:17:11.780
And then we can use this out type variable value in our eval chunk option.

00:17:12.500 --> 00:17:18.339
And now we're including both of these code chunks in our document, but only the code

00:17:18.339 --> 00:17:25.780
chunk that has that eval evaluated to true will actually render and be included in your

00:17:25.780 --> 00:17:26.180
report.

00:17:27.780 --> 00:17:33.300
So, here's some tools for styling and picking your colors and contrast.

00:17:34.339 --> 00:17:40.500
And you would include this in your YAML header for HTML output Word document.

00:17:40.500 --> 00:17:42.420
And these are listed in the resources.

00:17:43.219 --> 00:17:47.300
And I don't have time to talk about the browser developer tools.

00:17:47.300 --> 00:17:53.939
But this is here for you to double check your contrast ratios for your HTML reports.

00:17:55.300 --> 00:17:58.819
And what's really nifty is if you click on it, you can actually adjust the colors.

00:17:58.819 --> 00:18:00.180
But, again, I don't have time.

00:18:00.180 --> 00:18:07.859
So, the end result, though, is everybody gets their very own custom decision support tool.

00:18:07.859 --> 00:18:13.300
So, that's essentially what parameterized reports can be if you design them right.

00:18:13.300 --> 00:18:18.180
And provide all the context that's needed to understand those results.

00:18:18.739 --> 00:18:25.859
So, to recap, we learned a little bit of parameterized reporting 101.

00:18:26.819 --> 00:18:32.500
We saw that we can just use our data that has columns for each parameter.

00:18:33.380 --> 00:18:40.260
And then we made sure that our content is easily understandable and is accessible to

00:18:40.260 --> 00:18:41.459
all of our audience.

